## 1. Purpose
This policy defines how [COMPANY] grants, manages, and removes logical access to information systems and data so that access is limited to authorized individuals and processes with a legitimate business need. It implements the least-privilege and need-to-know principles required to protect the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of information assets, including Protected Health Information (PHI).

## 2. Scope
This policy applies to all workforce members, contractors, and non-human identities (service accounts, automation, CI/CD principals) that access [COMPANY] systems. It covers all in-scope systems, with particular emphasis on those that create, receive, maintain, or transmit PHI: the production SaaS application, the [AWS] environment (IAM / IAM Identity Center), [Snowflake] (RBAC), the [GitHub] organization, and federated [SaaS] applications fronted by the [IdP — e.g. Okta]. Authentication mechanics are governed by `identity-and-authentication-policy.md.template`; this policy governs *authorization*.

## 3. Policy
1. Access **shall** be granted on the principles of **least privilege** (the minimum permissions required to perform a role) and **need-to-know** (data access limited to what the role legitimately requires).
2. Access **shall** be **default-deny**: no access exists until explicitly granted through the authorization workflow in §6.
3. Access **shall** be granted to **roles, not individuals**, using Role-Based Access Control (RBAC). Standing entitlements are attached to defined roles; individuals receive entitlements only by assignment to a role.
4. Every account **shall** map to a single, identifiable owner. Shared or generic interactive accounts are prohibited (see `identity-and-authentication-policy.md.template`).
5. **Segregation of Duties (SoD)** **shall** be enforced so that no single individual can both authorize and execute a sensitive action without independent control (e.g., the requester of access may not also be its sole approver; the author of production code may not be its sole deployer where avoidable).
6. All access grants, changes, and revocations **shall** be authorized through the workflow in §6 and recorded as evidence.
7. Privileged and administrative access **shall** be additionally governed by `privileged-access-management.md.template`.
8. Joiner, mover, and leaver events **shall** be processed per `joiner-mover-leaver-procedure.md.template`, including timely revocation on termination.
9. All access entitlements **shall** be periodically recertified per `access-recertification-procedure.md.template`; access no longer required **shall** be revoked.
10. Access to PHI **shall** be restricted to the minimum necessary and **shall** be logged and monitored.
11. Access-control configurations (IAM policies, Snowflake role grants, GitHub permissions) **shall** be managed as code or through audited administrative tooling wherever feasible, and changes **shall** be reviewed.

## 4. Roles & Responsibilities
| Role | Responsibility |
|---|---|
| [Security Officer / CISO] | Owns this policy; defines the RBAC model and SoD matrix; oversees recertification. |
| [System / Resource Owners] | Define the roles and entitlements for their systems; approve access requests within their domain. |
| [Manager] | Initiates access requests for their reports; confirms ongoing business need at recertification. |
| [IT / Identity Administrators] | Execute provisioning and deprovisioning per approved requests; maintain the IdP and directory. |
| All Workforce | Use only access granted to them; do not share credentials; report excess or unneeded access. |

See `../governance/roles-and-responsibilities.md.template` for full role definitions.

## 5. RBAC, Account Types & Segregation of Duties
**Account types.** [COMPANY] recognizes the following account types, each with distinct controls:
- **Standard user accounts** — day-to-day workforce access, provisioned via the [IdP — e.g. Okta] and federated to downstream systems.
- **Privileged / administrative accounts** — elevated access governed by `privileged-access-management.md.template`; separate from daily-use accounts.
- **Service / non-human accounts** — used by applications, automation, and CI/CD; key-pair or workload identity authenticated (see `identity-and-authentication-policy.md.template`); owned by a named individual or team.
- **Emergency / break-glass accounts** — pre-provisioned, tightly controlled, logged, and used only under documented emergency procedures.
- **External / guest accounts** — contractors and vendors; time-bound and subject to third-party requirements (`../vendor/third-party-risk-management-policy.md.template`).

**RBAC model.** Each in-scope system defines named roles with documented entitlements:
- **[AWS]** — permissions assigned through IAM Identity Center permission sets / IAM roles mapped to job functions; no long-lived user access keys for human users; cross-account access via assumed roles.
- **[Snowflake]** — functional roles (e.g., analyst, engineer, read-only) built on a role hierarchy; access to PHI-bearing schemas restricted by role grants; warehouse and database privileges granted to roles, never directly to users.
- **[GitHub]** — team-based repository permissions; least-privilege repo roles (read / triage / write / maintain) assigned via teams; org-owner access minimized per the PAM policy.
- **[Application]** — in-app roles enforce least privilege over PHI and customer data.

**Segregation of duties.** A documented SoD matrix **shall** identify conflicting duty pairs (e.g., access approver vs. access administrator; developer vs. production deployer; security configuration vs. log/audit administration). Where complete separation is impractical (small teams), compensating controls (peer review, enhanced logging, after-the-fact review) **shall** be documented as an exception per §7.

## 6. Access Authorization Workflow
1. **Request** — A [Manager] or the individual submits an access request via [the access request system / ticketing tool], specifying the role or entitlement and business justification.
2. **Authorize** — The relevant [System / Resource Owner] (and, for PHI or privileged access, the [Security Officer]) approves or denies. The requester may not be the sole approver.
3. **Provision** — [IT / Identity Administrators] grant access by assigning the appropriate role/permission set; access is provisioned through the [IdP] and federation wherever supported.
4. **Record** — The approval, justification, and grant are retained as evidence to support recertification (`access-recertification-procedure.md.template`) and audit.
5. **Review & revoke** — Access is reviewed on schedule and revoked on role change or departure (`joiner-mover-leaver-procedure.md.template`).

## 7. Exceptions
Exceptions to this policy require documented risk acceptance per `../governance/exceptions-and-waivers.md.template`, approved by the [Security Officer], time-bound, and recorded in the exceptions log. SoD compensating controls are documented here.

## 8. Compliance, Monitoring & Enforcement
Compliance is verified through periodic access recertification, automated entitlement reporting (AWS IAM Access Analyzer / Identity Center reports, Snowflake `ACCOUNT_USAGE` grants views, GitHub access exports), and internal audit. Anomalous or unauthorized access is investigated under the incident response process. Violations are handled per `../people/hr-security-policy.md.template`, including the HIPAA workforce sanctions process (`../healthcare/sanctions-policy.md.template`).

